Unlike privacy coins like #Monero, every #Bitcoin transaction can be traced to its point of origin.

Privacy coins differ from regular cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin, litecoin and ethereum. To obfuscate user identities, coins like Monero mix-up and anonymize transactions as they are processed.

However, no two privacy coins are created equal.
Unlike Dash, privacy safeguards with Monero are not optional. All funds which are sent and received are anonymized as standard. When using Monero, anonymity is default.

Zcash uses two different types of wallet addresses: those starting with a "t" are transparent and details of the transaction similar to bitcoin can be viewed, whereas addresses beginning with a "z" are shielded transactions that provide user anonymity.

The Caesar cipher is named after Julius Caesar, who used it to protect his military communications. It's a substitution cipher, where each letter corresponds to another a number of positions forward or backward in the alphabet. A shift right of 5 would encode "Caesar" as "hfjxfw"

If you come across an encrypted message that seems to consist of boxes, dots and the occasional triangle then you've probably found yourself an example of the Pigpen cipher. This cipher has a fascinating history which includes the kabbala, secret orders, freemasons and pirates.

The Playfair cipher was invented in 1854. It is a polygraphic substitution cipher, which encrypts pairs of letters instead of single letters. This makes frequency analysis much more difficult, since there are around 600 combinations instead of 26.

The one-time pad is a theoretically unbreakable cipher. However, in practice it is of limited usability because it requires a pre-shared key of at least the same length as the message. Generating truly random keys and pre-sharing them securely are challenging problems.
